e=\"Back\"/>\n|staff             = 3,500+ (2015)<ref name=\"Seek\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/KU-seeks-applications-for-vice-chancellor/-/539550/2983268/-/nx0dlh/-/index.html|title=KU seeks applications for vice-chancellor to replace Olive Mugenda|date=3 December 2015|accessdate=25 March 2016 |first=Ouma |last=Wanzala |location=Nairobi\n|newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]]}}</ref> \n|affiliations      =[[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU,]],\n}}\n'''Kenyatta University''' ('''KU''') is a public [[research university]] with its main campus in both [[Nairobi County]] and [[Kiambu County]], [[Kenya]]. It acquired the status of university in 1985, being the third university after [[University of Nairobi]] (1970) and [[Moi University]] (1984). As of October 2014, it was one of 23 public universities in the country.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=1 December 2014|  url=http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20110930191006499|last=Nganga|publisher=University World News (UWN)| title=Kenya: Double Student Intake Kicks Off At Kenyatta|first=Gilbert\n|date=2 October 2011}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Location==\nThe main campus of Kenyatta University is at [[Kahawa]], [[Nairobi County]] in [[Kasarani Constituency]], approximately {{convert|18|km|mi}}, by road, northeast of the [[central business district]] of [[Nairobi]], the capital city of Kenya, off of the [[Thika Road|Nairobi-Thika Road]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=25 March 2016\n|url=http://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Kenya_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Nairobi%20Central%2C%20Nairobi%2C%20Kenya&toplace=AIESEC%20Kenyatta%20University%2C%20Nairobi%2C%20Kenya%2C&dt1=ChIJNe4z_9QQLxgRVVtoNpaFdCw&dt2=ChIJG4aOFgw_LxgRHqWXfzkSNhg |date=25 March 2016|title= Distance between Nairobi Central, Nairobi, Kenya and AIESEC Kenyatta University, Nairobi, Kenya| publisher=Globefeed.com (GFC)|last=GFC}}</ref> The coordinates of Kenyatta University main campus are 1\u00b010'50.0\"S, 36\u00b055'41.0\"E (Latitude:-1.180568; Longitude:36.928042).<ref>{{google maps\n|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/1%C2%B010'50.0%22S+36%C2%B055'41.0%22E/@-1.2157662,36.7765412,33053m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x0|accessdate=25 March 2016|title=Location of Kenyatta University Main Campus}}</ref>\n\nThe list of KU campuses includes the following locations:<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ku.ac.ke/index.php/explore/all-themes/ku-campuses \n |title=The Campuses of Kenyatta University \n |accessdate=25 March 2016 \n |date=25 March 2016 \n |publisher=Kenyatta University (KU) \n |last=KU \n |location=Nairobi \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321140552/http://www.ku.ac.ke/index.php/explore/all-themes/ku-campuses \n |archivedate=March 21, 2016 \n}}</ref>\n\n# Main Campus - [[Kahawa]], [[Nairobi]]\n# Ruiru Campus - [[Ruiru]]\n# Parkland Campus - [[Parklands, Nairobi|Parklands]]\n# Kitui Campus - [[Kwa Vonza]]\n# Mombasa Campus - [[Mombasa]]\n# City Centre Campus - [[Nairobi|Nairobi Central Business District]]\n# Nyeri Campus - [[Nyeri]]\n# Nakuru Campus - [[Nakuru]]\n# Kericho Campus - [[Kericho]]\n# Dadaab Campus -[[Dadaab]]\n# Embu Campus - [[Embu, Kenya|Embu]]\n# Arusha Campus - [[Arusha]], [[Tanzania]] -  Closed\n# Kigali Campus - [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]] - Closed<ref>{{cite web|first=Mugambi\n|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/Kenyatta-University-to-open-Rwanda-campus-next-year/-/539550/3011736/-/algdl6/-/index.html\n|title=Kenyatta University to open Rwanda campus next year\n|newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]]| location=Nairobi |last=Mutegi}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1965, the British government handed over the Templar Barracks in Kahawa, to the newly formed government of Kenya. The barracks were then converted into a college called '''Kenyatta College'''. In 1970, Kenyatta College became a constituent college of the [[University of Nairobi]], and its name changed to '''Kenyatta University College''', following an Act of Parliament.\n\nIn 1985, it was granted full university status and was renamed Kenyatta University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ku.ac.ke/index.php/contacts/87-about-ku/177-about-ku|title=Short History of Kenyatta University|last=KU|date=25 March 2016|publisher=Kenyatta University (KU)|location=Nairobi|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405140222/http://www.ku.ac.ke/index.php/contacts/87-about-ku/177-about-ku|archive-date=5 April 2016|url-status=|accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite law|title=Kenyatta University Act|number=|date=1985|url=http://kenyalaw.org/kl/fileadmin/pdfdownloads/Acts/KenyattaUniversityAct_Cap210C.pdf|article=|articletype=|ref=}}</ref>\n\nU.S. President [[Barack Obama]], whose late father, [[Barack Obama, Sr.]] (an economist) and paternal relatives are from Kenya, visited Kenya in 2015; while there, he visited one of the university's campuses.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=25 March 2016| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/27/world/africa/obama-calls-on-kenya-to-confront-its-problems.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=first-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news&_r=1|title= Obama Delivers Tough-Love Message to End Kenya Trip|date=26 July 2015 |last=Baker\n|first=Peter |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|location=New York City}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nAs of March 2016, the university has 12 campuses offering bachelor's degrees, master's degrees, and doctoral degrees. The degrees awarded include those in medicine and law. The university has open-learning, e-learning, school-based, part-time and full-time teaching. Kenyatta University is accredited by the Kenya Commission of University Education, the Inter-University Council for East Africa, the Africa Association of Universities, the International Association of Universities and the Commonwealth Universities.<ref>{{cite web\n |date=7 June 2013 \n |url=http://www.ku.ac.ke/index.php/about-ku/about-ku/accreditation \n |title=Accreditation of Kenyatta University \n |last=KU \n |accessdate=25 March 2016 \n |location=Nairobi \n |publisher=Kenyatta University (KU) \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428155535/http://www.ku.ac.ke/index.php/about-ku/about-ku/accreditation \n |archivedate=April 28, 2015 \n}}</ref>\n\n===Schools and institutes===\n{{asof|March 2016}}, the university maintains the following schools:<ref>{{cite web|title=The Schools of Kenyatta University|date=22 August 2013|url=http://www.ku.ac.ke/index.php/academics/schools|accessdate=25 March 2016|location=Nairobi|last=KU|publisher=Kenyatta University (KU)|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401104628/http://ku.ac.ke/index.php/academics/schools|archivedate=April 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n|+\n|School of Humanities and Social Sciences (2002)\n|School of Public Health (2004)\n|-\n|School of Visual And Performing Arts (2008)\n|School of Business(2005)\n|-\n|School of Education (1970)\n|School of Economics (1998)\n|-\n|School of Pure And Applied Sciences(2003)\n|School of Agriculture and Enterprise Development(1984)\n|-\n|School of Engineering And Technology (1985)\n|School of Law - Parklands(2009)\n|-\n|School of Environmental Studies (2003)\n|School of Medicine (2011)\n|-\n|School of Hospitality & Tourism(2010)\n|School of Virtual & Open Learning(2011)\n|-\n|School of Architecture and the Built Environment (2016) - Ruiru Campus\n|School of Creative, Film and Media Studies (2015) - Ruiru Campus\n|-\n|School of Nursing Sciences (2017)\n|}\nSchool of Security, Diplomacy and Peace Studies(2018)\n\n===Institutes and centers===\nThe university hosts institutes and centers such as;\n# Confucius Institute at Kenyatta University, \n# Africa Centre for Transformative and Inclusive Leadership (ACTIL)\n# Chandaria Business Innovations and Incubation Centre (CBIIC)\n# Center for Refugee Studies and Empowerment\n# Cisco Networking Academy\n\n=== Degrees and courses ===\nThe following courses are offered by the university and accredited by the [http://www.cue.or.ke/index.php/accredited-universities Commission for University Education] in Kenya (CUE)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cue.or.ke/index.php/accredited-universities|title=Programmes developed and mounted by Universities in Kenya in accordance with the Universities Act|website=www.cue.or.ke|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-10-20}}</ref>\n\nDoctorates and PhD - 14\n\nMaster's degree - 94\n\nBachelor's degree - 117\n\nPostgraduates Diploma - 12\n\n==Student life==\n\n===International students===\nThe Centre for International Programmes and Collaboration is a unit under the office of the Vice Chancellor, responsible for coordinating international activities, collaborations and linkages.\n\n===Athletics===\nKenyatta University partnered with [[International Association of Athletics Federations|IAAF]] as an athletics-village in the 2017 world under 18 championship Nairobi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wu18nairobi2017.com|title=IAAF World U18 Championships Nairobi 2017|website=www.wu18nairobi2017.com|language=en|access-date=2017-09-01}}</ref> The athletes were hosted in the Nyayo hostels and used the campus facilities for training.\n\nKenyatta University offers the following disciplines:\n\n====Men's sports====\n[[Association football|Football]], rugby, [[hockey]], [[volleyball]], netball, [[handball]], [[basketball]], [[tennis]], table tennis, squash, [[badminton]], [[chess]], scrabble, darts, boxing, bodybuilding, [[taekwondo]], swimming, athletics (track and field), scrabble, karate, [[Roll Ball]], woodball, judo, wrestling, Goalball, [[baseball]], softball.\n\n====Women's sports====\nFootball, rugby, hockey, volleyball, netball, handball, basketball, tennis, table tennis, squash, badminton, chess, scrabble, darts, boxing, fitness modelling, Taekwondo, swimming, athletics (track and field), Scrabble, Karate, [[Roll Ball]], woodball, Judo, goalball, baseball, softball Seminars Short \u2013 term Courses in coaching, Sports management, training and Sports leadership are offered.\n\n====Sports facilities====\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* Two swimming pools\n* One gymnasium\n* Five soccer fields\n* Eight tennis courts\n* Four volleyball courts\n* One rugby field\n* Two badminton courts\n* One squash court\n* Three netball fields\n* Two athletics & track fields(IAAF Track)\n* Three handball courts\n* Two hockey fields\n* Four basketball courts\n* Two common rooms for indoor sports & board games.\n}}\n\n====Sports achievements====\n* 2012 - National Champions, Kenya University Women's Games\n* 2011 - National Champions, Kenya University Games\n* 2010 - 3rd Best University, East Africa University Games\n* 2009 - National Champions, Kenya University Games\n* 2006 - 6th Best University, East Africa University Games\n* 2004 - 2nd Best University, East Africa University Games\n\n==Alumni==\n\nThe following individuals are some of the \"prominent alumni\" at the Kenyatta University website:<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=25 March 2016|last=KU\n|url=http://alumni.ku.ac.ke/|title=Kenyatta University: Alumni Board Members  |date=25 March 2016|location=Nairobi |publisher=Kenyatta University (KU)}}</ref>\n\n* [[Mwai Kibaki]] - former [[President of Kenya]], 2002 to 2013\n* [[Stephen Kalonzo Musyoka]] - former Vice President of Kenya\n* [[Jakaya Kikwete]] - President of the [[United Republic of Tanzania]], 2005 to 2015\n* [[Daniel arap Moi]] - former President of Kenya, 1978 to 2002\n* [[Benjamin Mkapa]] - former President of Tanzania, 1995 to 2005\n* Dr. Harris Mule - former [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of Kenyatta University\n* [[Mostafa Tolba|Dr. Mostafa Tolba]] - former Executive Director of the [[United Nations Environment Programme]]\n* Dr. Geoffrey William Griffin - founder Director of [[Starehe Boys' Centre and School]]\n* [[James Mwangi|Dr. James Mwangi]] - Managing Director and Chief Executive Officer, [[Equity Bank Group]]\n* Dr. Eddah Gachukia - Academic Director, Riara Group of Schools\n*[[Esther Ngumbi]] \u2013 Entomologist and winner of the 2018 [[Society for Experimental Biology]] Presidential Award\n* Professor Michael Bernard Kwesi - Professor, Department of Geography, Kenyatta University\n* Professor John Mutio - former Deputy Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs, Kenyatta University\n* Lawrence M. Mungai - former Registrar of Kenyatta University College\n* Professor James M. Waithaka - Professor and Deputy Principal, Kenyatta University College\n* Professor [[J. M. Mungai]] - former Vice-Chancellor, University of Nairobi.\n* [[Phillip Ndegwa]] - founding Chairman, Kenyatta University Council, 1985 to 1994.\n* [[Onesmo K. ole-MoiYoi]] - former Chairman, Kenyatta University Council, 1994 to 2010.\n* [[Daudi Kabaka]] - musician and Band Leader of Kenyatta University Band.\n\n==Notable staff and professors==\n# Prof Ahmed Hasanali - Professor (Chemical Ecology & Bioprospecting), ICIPE\n# Prof [[Mike Boit]] - Sports Science,Former athlete. Received an honorary Doctorate of Science (DSc) from the [[University of Glasgow]] in recognition of his contributions to the academic research of sports and its development in Kenya 2014\n# Prof. Edward Waswa Kisiang'ani - Historian, Political analyst/scientist and strategist.\n# Prof Olive Mugenda - Former Vice-Chancellor (2009-2016), Board Chair KU hospital.\n\n==Management==\nThe chancellor is [[Benson Wairegi]]. The [[Vice Chancellor]] is Professor Paul Wainaina. He replaced [[Olive Mugenda|Professor Olive Mugenda]], the first female Vice Chancellor of a [[public university]] in Kenya, who retired after the end of her tenure in January 2016.<ref name=\"New\"/><ref>{{cite web|date=25 March 2016\n|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/My-track-record-speaks-for-itself--says-Prof-Mugenda/-/539444/3132468/-/y6kmk6z/-/index.html|title= My track record speaks for itself, says Prof Mugenda|first=and Kiarie Njoroge | last=Mugambi Mutegi |access-date=8 February 2018\n|newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]] |location=Nairobi}}</ref> There are four Deputy Vice Chancellors and four Registrars, to assist the Vice Chancellor carry out his mandate.\n\nThe Deputy Vice Chancellors are:\n* DVC Academic Affairs: Professor John Okumu\n* DVC Administration: TBD\n* DVC Finance and Development: Professor Godfrey Mse\n* DVC Research, Innovation & Outreach: Professor F.K Gravenir\n\n==Businesses and investments==\nThe university owns and operates the following income-generating businesses and investments:<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=25 March 2015|date=23 March 2016\n|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Corporate-News/KU-plans-diversifying-into-commercial-dairy-farming/-/539550/3131092/-/11gppae/-/index.html\n|first=Mugambi |last=Mutegi |newspaper=[[Business Daily Africa]]\n|location=Nairobi|title=KU plans diversifying into commercial dairy farming}}</ref>\n\n# Kenyatta University Funeral Home\n# North Coast Beach Hotel - [[Mombasa]]\n# Uni-City Shopping Mall & Office Complex - Nairobi\n# Kenyatta University Conference Center - Nairobi (100 rooms)\n# Kenyatta University Bookstore - Nairobi \n# Television station KUTV\n# Kenyatta University Children's Hospital - Nairobi (Under construction)\n# Kenyatta University Dairy Farm - (In development)\n# [[Kenyatta University Hospital]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kuh.co.ke/|title=Kenyatta University Teaching Research & Referral Hospital|website=kuh.co.ke|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-09-01}}</ref> (KUH)\n\n==Views 2016==\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|width=300\n|height=250\n|lines=4\n|align=center\n|File:Kenyatta University Entrance.jpg|Kenyatta University, the main entrance, Nairobi 2016\n|File:KenyattaUnivLibrary.jpg|Kenyatta University, the main library, Nairobi 2016\n|File:KenyattaUnivCampanile.jpg|Kenyatta University, the Campanile, Nairobi 2016\n|File:KenyattaUnivAdmin.jpg|Kenyatta University, the Central Administration Complex, Nairobi 2016\n|File:KenyattaUnivComputerCentre.jpg|Kenyatta University, the student's computer centre, Nairobi 2016\n|File:KenyattaUnivEducationBd.jpg|Kenyatta University, the Education Building, Nairobi 2016\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.ku.ac.ke/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161114003450/http://www.machakosuniversity.ac.ke/ Machakos University College website]\n* [http://www.pu.ac.ke/ Pwani University college]\n* [http://www.edukenya.com More information about Colleges and Universities in Kenya]\n* [http://www.kenyaplex.com Leading Colleges and Universities in Kenya]\n{{Nairobi}}\n{{Kenyan universities}}\n\n[[Category:Kenyatta University| ]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Education in Nairobi]]\n[[Category:Education in Mombasa]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Jomo Kenyatta]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Kenya]]\n[[Category:1980s in Nairobi]]\n[[Category:Kiambu County]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenyatta_University"}
{"title_page": "University of the Sunshine Coast", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name            = USC Australia\n| image           = USC Logo Australia.jpg\n| caption         = Logo for USC - University of the Sunshine Coast\n| image_size      = \n| established     = 1994\n| type            = [[public university|Public]]\n| chancellor      = Air Chief Marshal [[Angus Houston|Sir Angus Houston]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AK|AFC|sep=,}}\n| vice_chancellor = Professor Greg Hill\n| students        = ca. 16,592 enrolled during 2017\n| city            = [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]]\n| state           = [[Queensland]]\n| country         = Australia\n| campus          = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n| website         = {{url|www.usc.edu.au}}\n| motto           = \n| faculty         = 961 (full-time equivalent as at 2017)\n| affiliations    = [[Regional Universities Network]]Im running out of time \n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Sunshine Coast''' (USC) is a [[public university]] based on the [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland]], Australia. After opening with 524 students in 1996 as the '''Sunshine Coast University College''', it was later renamed the '''University of the Sunshine Coast''' in 1999.\n\nThe university has a flagship campus at [[Sippy Downs]] on the Sunshine Coast, with more campuses at [[Hervey Bay]] on the [[Fraser Coast]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/usq-to-transfer-fraser-coast-campus-in-hervey-bay-to-usc/news-story/8de2478417724fa0ced41f59352c9111|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|last=|first=|date=|website=The Australian|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> Gympie,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gympietimes.com.au/news/usc-gympie-celebrates-first-education-graduates/3390871/|title=USC Gympie celebrates first education graduates|last=PRESTON|first=JOSH|date=|work=Gympie Times|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> Caboolture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/caboolture-university-campus-to-switch-from-qut-to-usc-20170615-gwrrq7.html|title=Caboolture university campus to switch from QUT to USC|last=Mitchell-Whittington|first=Amy|date=2017-06-15|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> and [[South Bank, Queensland|South Bank]] in [[Brisbane]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/usc-welcome-students-brisbane-campus/2935545/|title=USC to welcome students at Brisbane campus|last=|first=|date=|work=Sunshine Coast Daily|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> USC also has study hubs in [[Noosa]] and North Lakes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qtac.edu.au/courses-institutions/universities-tafes-colleges/usc|title=USC - QTAC|last=|first=|date=|website=QTAC|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> In 2020, USC will open a full-service campus at [[Petrie, Queensland|Petrie]] in Moreton Bay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moretonbay.qld.gov.au/themill/|title=Thriving new destination - The Mill at Moreton Bay|last=|first=|date=|website=Moreton Bay Regional Council|language=en-au|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/questnews/moreton/construction-officially-starts-on-australias-newest-university-as-first-courses-are-revealed/news-story/49e019db8338b6388560ba3d1fb409ec|title=Couriermail.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Courier Mail for exclusive stories|last=|first=|date=|website=Courier Mail|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n[[File:USC Sippy Downs campus 2019.jpg|thumb|USC Sippy Downs campus 2019]]\n\n[[Undergraduate]] and [[postgraduate]] (coursework and higher degree by research) programs are offered in both faculties (Arts, Business, and Law; Science, Health, Education and Engineering), with study areas divided into seven disciplines: business, IT and tourism; creative industries, design and communication; education; engineering and science; health, nursing and sport sciences; humanities, psychology and social sciences; and law and criminology.\n\nThe university is listed on the [[Commonwealth Register of Institutions and Courses for Overseas Students]].\n\n==History==\nThe first discussions about a university for the Sunshine Coast region began in 1973. In 1989, the Australian Federal Government approved its establishment. On 1 July 1994 the Queensland Parliament passed the ''Sunshine Coast University College Act 1994''.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Establishment.htm Establishment of the University of the Sunshine Coast] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010054624/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Establishment.htm |date=10 October 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Sunshine Coast University College Act 1994|url=http://www.legislation.qld.gov.au/LEGISLTN/ACTS/1994/94AC016.pdf|accessdate=25 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe university was established in 1994, opening in 1996 as the Sunshine Coast University College. ''The University of the Sunshine Coast Act 1998''<ref>{{Citation | title = University of the Sunshine Coast Act 1998 | url = http://www.legislation.qld.gov.au/LEGISLTN/ACTS/1998/98AC047.pdf | accessdate = 25 May 2009}}</ref> was passed in Queensland Parliament on 19 November of that year, legislating the independent status of the university. The university changed to its current name of the University of the Sunshine Coast (USC) in 1999. It was created by the [[Government of Australia|Australian Government]] to serve the growing population of the Sunshine Coast region, north of [[Brisbane]], in Queensland. The University of the Sunshine Coast is the first greenfield university established in Australia since 1971.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://campusmorningmail.com.au/news/new-campus-for-queensland/|title=New campus for Queensland|last=Matchett|first=Stephen|date=20 September 2019|website=Campus Morning Mail|access-date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe inaugural [[vice-chancellor]] was [[Paul Thomas (academic)|Professor Paul Thomas]], {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}}, who took office with effect from 1 January 1996, having spent an earlier period as planning president. [[Tony Fitzgerald|Justice Gerald \u201cTony\u201d Fitzgerald]] was the university's inaugural chancellor, followed by pastoralist Ian Kennedy, AO, who was USC's second chancellor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mbrit.com.au/blog-news/former-defence-chief-appointed-new-usc-chancellor|title=Former Defence chief appointed new USC Chancellor {{!}} Business Moreton Bay Region|website=www.mbrit.com.au|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/it-took-a-combined-effort-to-make-our-university-a/3206099/|title=It took a combined effort to make our university a reality|work=Sunshine Coast Daily|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref> Air Chief Marshal [[Angus Houston|Sir Angus Houston]] AK, AFC (Ret\u2019d) became the university's fourth chancellor when he was appointed to the role in 2017 after John Dobson OAM retired from the position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/sir-angus-houston-appointed-university-of-the-sunshine-coast-chancellor-20170303-gupuzb.html|title=Sir Angus Houston appointed University of the Sunshine Coast chancellor|last=Mitchell-Whittington|first=Amy|date=2017-03-03|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mbrit.com.au/blog-news/former-defence-chief-appointed-new-usc-chancellor|title=Former Defence chief appointed new USC Chancellor {{!}} Business Moreton Bay Region|website=www.mbrit.com.au|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> Sir Angus remains the University's current chancellor.\n\nThe student body has grown consistently since the university opened in 1996 with an intake of 524 students. In 2017, USC had 16,692 students enrolled, a 13.6 percent increase on the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/documents/tableOffice/TabledPapers/2018/5618T437.pdf|title=Qld Parliament tabled documents|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe university introduced paid parking at its Sippy Downs campus from February 2013, a move that garnered a negative response from some students and staff. Of the university's 2,400 parking spaces, approximately 450 (located {{convert|1|km|mi}} from the centre of campus) remain as free parking.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox Australian university ranking\n| UniName    = \n| QS_W       = \n| QS_W_GER   = \n| THES_W     = 501\u2013600\n| ARWU_W     = \n| USNWR_W    = \n| LEIDEN_W   = \n| QS_AUS     = \n| THES_AUS   = \n| ARWU_AUS   = \n| USNWR_AUS  = \n| LEIDEN_AUS = \n| ERA_AUS    = 35<ref>{{cite news|title=All unis winners in research audit|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/all-unis-winners-in-research-audit/news-story/a592cd109c087503ba4ea49cdf56c561|accessdate=21 February 2017|work=[[The Australian]]|date=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nSince 2010, USC has been the only public institution in Queensland to receive five stars for teaching quality in the independently ranked ''Hobson's Good Universities Guide''. In the 2010 edition of the guide, the university also earned five stars for staff qualifications and graduates' satisfaction with the generic skills they learned while studying.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/MediaPublications/News/MoreNews/UniversitiesGuide2010.htm USC gains top marks for teaching quality] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815182126/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/MediaPublications/News/MoreNews/UniversitiesGuide2010.htm |date=15 August 2009 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- independent sourcing for a claim such as this, please --></ref>{{update inline|date=November 2013}}\n\nIn the 2011 edition, the university also earned five stars for graduate satisfaction with the generic skills learned while studying, and four stars for access by equity groups, Indigenous enrolments, gender balance, and for graduates' satisfaction with their overall university experience.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2010News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm USC gains five stars for teaching quality] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928162534/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2010News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm |date=28 September 2011 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- independent sourcing for a claim such as this, please --></ref> However, the university only received one star for research grants, research intensity, toughness to get in, cultural diversity of the student body, success in getting a job, graduate starting salary and positive graduate outcomes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gooduniguide.com.au/ratings/compare/SUNSHINE_COAST?studyType=UG&institutionName=University%20of%20the%20sunshine%20coast&actionSearch=Search |title=How Sunshine Coast rates and compares |publisher=Gooduniguide.com.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>{{update inline|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe 2012 edition of the guide, released in August 2011, also awarded the university five stars for its graduates' satisfaction with the generic skills they gained while at university, and for Indigenous participation. The university scored four stars for access by equity groups, gender balance, and for graduates' satisfaction with their overall university experience. Its ratings for graduates' satisfaction also remained the highest awarded to any public university in Queensland.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2011News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm USC gains five stars for teaching] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104201647/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2011News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm |date=4 November 2011 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- independent sourcing for a claim such as this, please --></ref>\n\nIn 2007 the [[Australian Universities Quality Agency]] (AUQA) audited USC as part of their assessment of all Australian universities. AUQA is a national agency that operates independently of governments and the higher education sector. The report commended USC for \"its significant achievements since inception\" and awarded USC commendations for the quality of the university's learning and teaching, student support services, workplace integrated learning program and degree approval process. The Headstart Program \u2013 a program allowing Year 11 and 12 school students to study one or more courses at the University, while still completing secondary school \u2013 and Global Opportunities Program \u2013 the University's study abroad were also acknowledged in the assessment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.auqa.edu.au/qualityaudit/reports/auditreport_usc_2007.doc/ |title=Australian Universities Quality Agency Audit 2007 \u2013 USC |access-date=27 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226112337/http://www.auqa.edu.au/qualityaudit/reports/auditreport_usc_2007.doc |archive-date=26 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nGraduates have consistently rated the university highly for educational experience, with a 92 percent satisfaction rating in the 2007 Course Experience Questionnaire.<ref>2007 Course Experience Questionnaire, conducted by Graduate Careers Australia \u2013 Overall Satisfaction Index, broad agreement{{Vague|date=February 2013}}<!-- Where is this published? --></ref>{{update inline|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe university's Global Opportunities Program received an award from the Queensland government at the Celebrating International Education and Training Industry Showcase in August 2007<ref>[http://www.premiers.qld.gov.au/Key_activities_information_and_services/International_students/Industry_update/Showcase/2007_Industry_Showcase/ Department of the Premier and Cabinet \u2013 2007 Industry Showcase] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080728170145/http://www.premiers.qld.gov.au/Key_activities_information_and_services/International_students/Industry_update/Showcase/2007_Industry_Showcase/ |date=28 July 2008 }}</ref> for promoting internationalisation.\n\nIn March 2008 the university was one of 99 organisations nationally and one of 10 in Queensland to earn an Employer of Choice for Women citation.<ref>[http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/Organisation_List_08.asp/ 2008 Employer of Choice for Women list] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090526084903/http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/Organisation_List_08.asp/ |date=26 May 2009 }}</ref> The citations are awarded annually by the federal government's [[Equal Opportunity for Women in the Workplace Agency]] (EOWA). It has received the citation for six consecutive years to 2010.<ref>[http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/2010/Documents/EOCFW_Breakdown_2010.pdf 2010 Employer of Choice for Women list] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001142540/http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/2010/Documents/EOCFW_Breakdown_2010.pdf |date=1 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nSince 2006, the university has been awarded 17 citations from the Australian Learning and Teaching Council, recognising outstanding contributions to student learning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=All&state=All&tid= |title=Office for Learning and Teaching &#124; Welcome |publisher=Altc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823032108/http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=All&state=All&tid= |archive-date=23 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Six of the citations were awarded in 2009, with a further six citations awarded in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=2010&state=All&tid= |title=Office for Learning and Teaching &#124; Welcome |publisher=Altc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725154659/http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=2010&state=All&tid= |archive-date=25 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2011, a further five USC staff earned ALTC citations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=2011&state=All&tid= |title=Office for Learning and Teaching &#124; Welcome |publisher=Altc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Campus and locations ==\n\nThe main University of the Sunshine Coast campus is at [[Sippy Downs, Queensland]]. The university also has teaching facilities in [[Noosa]], and operates an education and research facility at Dilli Village on [[Fraser Island]]. The Sippy Downs campus is about {{convert|100|km|mi}} north of Brisbane. It is a 100-hectare flora and fauna reserve, and borders the [[Mooloolah River National Park]].\n\nThe Sippy Downs site was previously a [[sugar cane]] farm, at the geographical heart of the Sunshine Coast and its shires, close to the [[Bruce Highway]] and other major transport routes.\n\nThe buildings on campus have received 30 awards<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Architecture/Stages.htm Architecture awards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121054735/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Architecture/Stages.htm |date=21 November 2008 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No. INDEPENDENT sources for claims such as this, please. --></ref> for planning, architecture and construction. In 2000 the university received the [[Royal Australian Institute of Architects]] President's Award,{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} and in 1997 the Library was awarded the [[Sir Zelman Cowen]] Award for Public Buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://architectureau.com/articles/sir-zelman-cowen-award-for-public-buildings-6/|title=Sir Zelman Cowen Award for Public Buildings|work=ArchitectureAU|access-date=11 August 2017|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nAll buildings on campus focus on environmentally sustainable design to suit the subtropical climate of the Sunshine Coast. Buildings have been designed for passive lighting and natural ventilation to minimise the use of non-renewable energy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architecture.com.au/awards_search?option=showaward&entryno=2007040540 |title=Australian Institute of Architects \u2013 University of the Sunshine Coast Building H |publisher=Architecture.com.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architectus.com.au/index.php?page=1014 |title=University of the Sunshine Coast Chancellery |publisher=Architectus |date=29 August 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, the university opened two new buildings, the A$12 million science building and A$13 million chancellery. In July 2007, the A$10 million indoor sports stadium was opened by Federal Education, Science and Training Minister [[Julie Bishop]]. A year later, [[Treasurer of Australia|Federal Treasurer]] [[Wayne Swan]] opened the A$13 million Health and Sport Centre, which has testing and research laboratories, a gymnasium and public psychology clinic.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Milestones/2007.htm Milestones 2007-2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007073249/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Milestones/2007.htm |date=7 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, construction started on a $5 million semi-industrial shared space facility for engineering and paramedic science students. This opened in May 2011 and has specialised equipment and large, open spaces suitable for medical emergency simulations and a wide variety of engineering tests and experiments. It also has several laboratories and tutorial rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/Boost-for-Engineering-Paramedic-Science.htm |title=Boost for engineering, paramedic science |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date=22 August 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144657/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/Boost-for-Engineering-Paramedic-Science.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also in August 2010, the construction of a child care centre on campus was announced, which will provide 75 child care spaces from early 2011.{{Vague|date=February 2013}}<!-- Now in 2013, does this centre exist, or were plans dropped? --><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/child-care-centre-to-be-built-at-usc.htm |title=Childcare centre to be built at USC campus |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144749/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/child-care-centre-to-be-built-at-usc.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, construction started on the university pool complex, which includes a 50m heated Olympic swimming pool for research and community use. The complex was officially opened on 19 October 2011, by Queensland Sport Minister Phil Reeves. Funding for the $2.1 million project was provided by the [[Government of Queensland|Queensland State Government]], the university, community donations, and through in-kind support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/minister-to-launch-usc-pool-construction.htm |title=Minister to launch USC pool construction |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144828/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/minister-to-launch-usc-pool-construction.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Art gallery===\n[[File:USC Sculpture BETWEEN with USC Sport Centre in background.jpg|thumb|upright|Leonard Sabol, ''Between'' sculpture with USC Health and Sport Centre in background]]\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast Gallery hosts a range of exhibitions focusing on contemporary art and design. The annual exhibition program includes:\n*new media (including computer-based design)\n*photography\n*painting, drawing and sculpture\n*illustration\n*student exhibitions\n\nThe gallery is in the heart of the university campus, with more than half of the annual attendance being educational visitors (USC students and staff, U3A, TAFE, primary and high school students).<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/about/ USC Art Gallery.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104203538/http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/about/ |date=4 November 2011 }} Retrieved 13 December 2011</ref>\n\n====University art and sculpture collection====\nSince its inception, the University of the Sunshine Coast has worked to develop an art collection focusing on contemporary Australian art with an emphasis on Queensland artists. Many of these works can be viewed throughout the University campus. The University collection includes several sculptures in public spaces on the campus.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/collection/collection.htm#sculpture USC Art and Sculpture] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327143832/http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/collection/collection.htm#sculpture |date=27 March 2012 }} Retrieved 13 December 2011</ref>\n\nThe University's collection of contemporary Australian Art includes one of the most significant collections of Western and Central Desert Australian Aboriginal Art on the Sunshine Coast.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/NR/rdonlyres/475E6C14-060C-46B9-B088-D071F0C4D5DE/0/WesternDesertEducationResource.pdf Western and Central Desert Australian Aboriginal Art on the Sunshine Coast] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419143113/http://www.usc.edu.au/NR/rdonlyres/475E6C14-060C-46B9-B088-D071F0C4D5DE/0/WesternDesertEducationResource.pdf |date=19 April 2013 }} Retrieved 13 December 2011.{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, you need an INDEPENDENT source for any claim that X is one of the most significant examples of Y.--></ref>\n\n===Netball stadium===\nThe university features an indoor arena used often for [[Netball]] matches and other sporting activities. Since February 2017 the arena has been the home stadium for [[Suncorp Super Netball|National Netball League]] team [[Sunshine Coast Lightning]]. The arena has a seating capacity of 2,200 and features broadcasting facilities and several corporate boxes.<ref name=Ref1>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/our-new-teams-striking-display-of-confidence/3078352/|title=Our new team's striking display of confidence|work=[[Sunshine Coast Daily]]|date=18 August 2016}}</ref> As a result of growing demand for the Lightning amongst the public, the venue was upgraded to 3,000 seats and also featured new change rooms, a function room, public bathrooms and an improved sound system; all of which was completed in May 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com.au/netball/story/_/id/25388195/lightning-buoyed-stadium-upgrade|title=Lightning buoyed by stadium upgrade|work=ESPN Netball|date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n\nIn 2012, the faculty structure at the university was revised, from three faculties each with a different number of schools contained therein, to two, each with three schools:\n\n*Faculty of Arts and Business\n**School of Business\n**School of Communication\n**School of Social Sciences\n*Faculty of Science, Health, Education and Engineering\n**School of Health and Sport Sciences\n**School of Nursing and Midwifery\n**School of Science, Education and Engineering\n\nThe University Council is the governing body with the chancellor presiding over council meetings. The council has 19 members including the chancellor drawn from the university staff, student body and wider community.\n\nThe academic board is the university's senior academic body. It advises the council concerning teaching, scholarship and research matters, formulates proposals for the academic policies of the university, monitors the academic activities of the university's faculties, and promotes and encourages scholarship and research at the university.\n\n== Research ==\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast's research focus is on regional engagement{{Vague|date=February 2013}}<!-- Sounds vaguely impressive, but what does it actually mean? --> and sustainability issues. In 2009, research efforts concentrated on applied genetics in primary production, regional sustainability and the health professions.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} The university has two core research groups; the GeneCology Research Group and the Sustainability Research Centre and an engagement centre, the Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise.\n\nThe USC Research Bank provides open access to the University of the Sunshine Coast's research output. The database ensures the research output of the university is accessible to local, national and international communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://research.usc.edu.au/vital/access/manager/ |title=USC Research Bank |publisher=Research.usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=28 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708153317/http://research.usc.edu.au/vital/access/manager/ |archive-date=8 July 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe university's research centres actively seek grants and funding, with the Sustainability Research Centre securing more than $2 million in funding in 2008, leading to the submission of more than 100 research papers.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} $1.3 million of that funding was drawn from the CSIRO's Collaborative Fund. In May 2009, a separate research team secured an AUSAID grant worth more than $500,000.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nIn June 2011 the university was announced as one of 12 projects to receive Australian government funding under the Collaborative Research Networks (CRN) program. In the period 2011 to 2014 the university will receive $5.45 million to fund research in water, sustainability, forestry and aquaculture.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/newsevents/news/2011news/usc-receives-5.45-million-to-boost-research.htm USC receives $5.45 million to boost research]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, you need independent sourcing for this kind of claim --></ref>\n\n=== Australian Research Council grants ===\nThe university received two [[Australian Research Council]] Discovery grants, worth more than $1 million, in the 2012 funding round announced in November 2011:\n* Scott Cummins was awarded a $656,377 ARC Future Fellowship for his study of primordial germ cell migration in perciform fish, titled: \"Decoding the rules of fate, attraction and cell migration in perciform fish\". The ARC grant will be coupled with Dr Cummins' ARC Discovery Project Grant for $145,000 over 2012 to 2014 for research into snail hypometabolism, enabling him to build a significant team of researchers conducting world-class research in the field of the biological sciences.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n* Roland De Marco, Pro Vice-Chancellor for Research and joint chief investigator in a project called \u201cNew mesoporous materials for use in high temperature proton exchange fuel cell membranes\u201d, gained a three-year ARC Discovery Project grant of $420,000, with $40,000 each year going to support a PhD student at the university. The research involves using [[synchrotron radiation]] techniques to develop innovative fuel cell materials with the potential to provide high energy and high stability alcohol fuel cells.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nOther 2011 ARC funding:\n* Kate Mounsey won a $375,000 competitive grant for research into the contagious skin infection, scabies, titled: \"A porcine model to provide new insights on scabies immunopathology\". Her study was one of 277 projects selected from 2,159 applications nationally for funding under the ARC's new Discovery Early Career Researcher Award (DECRA) scheme. The ARC grant will be coupled with Dr Mounsey's award of a National Health and Medical Research Council (NHMRC) Project grant of $483,510 (in collaboration with USC's Associate Professor Shelley Walton) on a related project over the same timeframe.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n* The university was announced as a partner in three successful ARC Linkage Infrastructure Equipment and Facilities grants, involving Cummins (via the [[University of Queensland]]), De Marco (via [[Curtin University]]) and Senior Lecturer in Environmental Microbiology, Ipek Kurtboke (via the University of Queensland).{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\n=== Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise ===\nThe Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise (CHASE) undertakes research and related activities in preventative health and rehabilitation, and understanding and enhancing sports performance. Projects include consultancies and tenders, conducting short courses and conferences and contributing to policy debate in areas such as biomechanical assessment, physiological profiling, sports coach education, and the implementation of healthy programs.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/Research/atUSC/Centres/CHASE/ The Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211180638/http://www.usc.edu.au/Research/atUSC/Centres/CHASE/ |date=11 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== GeneCology Research Group ===\nThe GeneCology Research Group operates in the areas of genetics, ecology, genomics and physiology and the interaction between these. The research group researches sustainable production of aquaculture, horticulture and forestry systems, biodiversity conservation and sustainable urban forestry and horticulture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/GeneCology/ |title=The GeneCology Research Group |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date=10 September 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104201310/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/GeneCology/ |archive-date=4 November 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Professor in Aquaculture Biotechnology Abigail Elizur and Associate Professor in Aquaculture Genetics Wayne Knibb were involved in a project that resulted in the first-ever captive spawning of Southern Bluefin Tuna.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2009News/Invention261109.htm |title=USC research features in ''Time Magazine'' |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144900/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2009News/Invention261109.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The project was voted the second most important innovation of the year by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', behind [[NASA]]'s [[Ares I|Ares rocket]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1934027_1934003_1933946,00.html|title=The 50 Best Inventions of 2009 \u2013 The Tank-Bred Tuna|publisher=Time.com|date=12 November 2009|accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Sustainability Research Centre ===\nThe Sustainability Research Centre focuses on sustainable communities and sustainable environments, and the institutions that relate to them. The research focus is based around coastal management, climate change, water management, natural and cultural heritage, innovation, adaptive growth, and community wellbeing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/SustainabilityResearchCentre/ |title=The Sustainability Research Centre |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104200642/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/SustainabilityResearchCentre/ |archive-date=4 November 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== University-based organisations ==\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast has one subsidiary company \u2013 Innovation Centre Sunshine Coast Pty Ltd. At the northern end of the campus, this is the first stage of a planned technology park precinct for Sippy Downs.<ref>{{Citation| url = http://www.business.sunshinecoast.qld.gov.au/sitePage.cfm?code=sc-bus-and-tech-precinct/| title = Sunshine Coast Regional Council current projects \u2013 Sunshine Coast Business and Technology Precinct| accessdate = 25 May 2009| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706122121/http://www.business.sunshinecoast.qld.gov.au/sitePage.cfm?code=sc-bus-and-tech-precinct%2F| archive-date = 6 July 2011| url-status = dead}}</ref> The Innovation Centre comprises a [[business incubator]] for start-up technology businesses and a [[business accelerator]] for established technology, knowledge-based, and professional service firms.\n\nThe Innovation Centre provides serviced office space, high speed optical fibre Internet connection, business development coaching and support. As of July 2010, the Innovation Centre has supported the start-up and growth of around 80 businesses, mainly in ICT, cleantech and creative industry sectors.<ref>[http://www.innovation-centre.com.au/company_all Innovation Centre \u2013 companies] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814160445/http://www.innovation-centre.com.au/company_all |date=14 August 2009 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, you need independent sourcing for a claim such as this. --></ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main list|List of University of the Sunshine Coast people}}\n\nThe current chancellor  of the university is Air Chief Marshall Sir Angus Houston, a retired senior officer of the Royal Australian Air Force. Professor Greg Hill was appointed vice chancellor of the university on 1 January 2011.\n\n== Student accommodation ==\nThree student accommodation complexes are next to the campus in Chancellor Park. Varsity Apartments, UniCentral and The Village are privately owned and operated. All are within walking distance of the campus, linked by pedestrian pathways.\n\nEach accommodation complex has furnished apartments, some with Internet connection. The general layout in an apartment is a shared kitchen and living room, with four single bedrooms, each with its own bathroom and toilet. The complexes are gated and have barbecues, pools and outdoor sports courts (such as tennis/basketball and volleyball). Many of these units are shared units, however each student has his/her own bedroom and bathroom, only sharing the main living spaces. Many complexes also mix the residents between local and international students for a well engaged cross cultural experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.varsityapartments.com.au/accommodation/ |title=Apartments |publisher=Varsity Apartments |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Apply Now |url=http://www.unicentral.net.au/facilities |title=Student Accommodation Facilities |publisher=UniCentral |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thevillage.net.au/Facilities.html |title=Accommodation |publisher=The Village |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nUniversity of the Sunshine Coast is serviced by [[TransLink (South East Queensland)|TransLink]] bus routes, operated by [[Sunbus Sunshine Coast|Sunbus]]. Services depart to Caloundra, Nambour, Maroochydore and Kawana, with connecting services to Noosa at Maroochydore's [[Sunshine Plaza bus station|Sunshine Plaza]] interchange, and connecting to rail services at [[Landsborough railway station, Queensland|Landsborough Station]]. Services enter and depart from the new [[University of the Sunshine Coast Bus Station, Queensland|bus station]] via the Green Link.<ref>[http://www.translink.com.au/greenlink.php About the University of the Sunshine Coast bus station and green link] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090720114024/http://www.translink.com.au/greenlink.php |date=20 July 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Queensland}}\n*[[List of universities in Australia]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|University of the Sunshine Coast}}\n*{{official website|http://www.usc.edu.au/}}\n*[http://www.universitiesaustralia.edu.au/ Universities Australia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20011006211147/http://www.innovation-centre.com.au/ Innovation Centre Sunshine Coast]\n\n{{Australian universities}}\n{{Australian university groups}}\n{{CDIO}}\n{{Sunshine Coast Lightning}}\n{{Suncorp Super Netball venues}}\n\n{{Coord|26|43|01|S|153|03|44|E|display=title|type:edu_dim:5km}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunshine Coast, University Of The}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Buderim]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:University of the Sunshine Coast| ]]\n[[Category:Sunshine Coast Lightning]]\n[[Category:Schools in Queensland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name            = USC Australia\n| image           = USC Logo Australia.jpg\n| caption         = Logo for USC - University of the Sunshine Coast\n| image_size      = \n| established     = 1994\n| type            = [[public university|Public]]\n| chancellor      = Air Chief Marshal [[Angus Houston|Sir Angus Houston]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AK|AFC|sep=,}}\n| vice_chancellor = Professor Greg Hill\n| students        = ca. 16,592 enrolled during 2017\n| city            = [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]]\n| state           = [[Queensland]]\n| country         = Australia\n| campus          = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n| website         = {{url|www.usc.edu.au}}\n| motto           = \n| faculty         = 961 (full-time equivalent as at 2017)\n| affiliations    = [[Regional Universities Network]]\n}}\n\nThe '''University of the Sunshine Coast''' (USC) is a [[public university]] based on the [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland]], Australia. After opening with 524 students in 1996 as the '''Sunshine Coast University College''', it was later renamed the '''University of the Sunshine Coast''' in 1999.\n\nThe university has a flagship campus at [[Sippy Downs]] on the Sunshine Coast, with more campuses at [[Hervey Bay]] on the [[Fraser Coast]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/usq-to-transfer-fraser-coast-campus-in-hervey-bay-to-usc/news-story/8de2478417724fa0ced41f59352c9111|title=Subscribe to The Australian {{!}} Newspaper home delivery, website, iPad, iPhone & Android apps|last=|first=|date=|website=The Australian|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> Gympie,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gympietimes.com.au/news/usc-gympie-celebrates-first-education-graduates/3390871/|title=USC Gympie celebrates first education graduates|last=PRESTON|first=JOSH|date=|work=Gympie Times|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> Caboolture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/caboolture-university-campus-to-switch-from-qut-to-usc-20170615-gwrrq7.html|title=Caboolture university campus to switch from QUT to USC|last=Mitchell-Whittington|first=Amy|date=2017-06-15|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> and [[South Bank, Queensland|South Bank]] in [[Brisbane]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/usc-welcome-students-brisbane-campus/2935545/|title=USC to welcome students at Brisbane campus|last=|first=|date=|work=Sunshine Coast Daily|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en}}</ref> USC also has study hubs in [[Noosa]] and North Lakes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qtac.edu.au/courses-institutions/universities-tafes-colleges/usc|title=USC - QTAC|last=|first=|date=|website=QTAC|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref> In 2020, USC will open a full-service campus at [[Petrie, Queensland|Petrie]] in Moreton Bay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moretonbay.qld.gov.au/themill/|title=Thriving new destination - The Mill at Moreton Bay|last=|first=|date=|website=Moreton Bay Regional Council|language=en-au|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.couriermail.com.au/questnews/moreton/construction-officially-starts-on-australias-newest-university-as-first-courses-are-revealed/news-story/49e019db8338b6388560ba3d1fb409ec|title=Couriermail.com.au {{!}} Subscribe to The Courier Mail for exclusive stories|last=|first=|date=|website=Courier Mail|language=en|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n[[File:USC Sippy Downs campus 2019.jpg|thumb|USC Sippy Downs campus 2019]]\n\n[[Undergraduate]] and [[postgraduate]] (coursework and higher degree by research) programs are offered in both faculties (Arts, Business, and Law; Science, Health, Education and Engineering), with study areas divided into seven disciplines: business, IT and tourism; creative industries, design and communication; education; engineering and science; health, nursing and sport sciences; humanities, psychology and social sciences; and law and criminology.\n\nThe university is listed on the [[Commonwealth Register of Institutions and Courses for Overseas Students]].\n\n==History==\nThe first discussions about a university for the Sunshine Coast region began in 1973. In 1989, the Australian Federal Government approved its establishment. On 1 July 1994 the Queensland Parliament passed the ''Sunshine Coast University College Act 1994''.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Establishment.htm Establishment of the University of the Sunshine Coast] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010054624/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Establishment.htm |date=10 October 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Sunshine Coast University College Act 1994|url=http://www.legislation.qld.gov.au/LEGISLTN/ACTS/1994/94AC016.pdf|accessdate=25 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe university was established in 1994, opening in 1996 as the Sunshine Coast University College. ''The University of the Sunshine Coast Act 1998''<ref>{{Citation | title = University of the Sunshine Coast Act 1998 | url = http://www.legislation.qld.gov.au/LEGISLTN/ACTS/1998/98AC047.pdf | accessdate = 25 May 2009}}</ref> was passed in Queensland Parliament on 19 November of that year, legislating the independent status of the university. The university changed to its current name of the University of the Sunshine Coast (USC) in 1999. It was created by the [[Government of Australia|Australian Government]] to serve the growing population of the Sunshine Coast region, north of [[Brisbane]], in Queensland. The University of the Sunshine Coast is the first greenfield university established in Australia since 1971.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://campusmorningmail.com.au/news/new-campus-for-queensland/|title=New campus for Queensland|last=Matchett|first=Stephen|date=20 September 2019|website=Campus Morning Mail|access-date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe inaugural [[vice-chancellor]] was [[Paul Thomas (academic)|Professor Paul Thomas]], {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}}, who took office with effect from 1 January 1996, having spent an earlier period as planning president. [[Tony Fitzgerald|Justice Gerald \u201cTony\u201d Fitzgerald]] was the university's inaugural chancellor, followed by pastoralist Ian Kennedy, AO, who was USC's second chancellor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mbrit.com.au/blog-news/former-defence-chief-appointed-new-usc-chancellor|title=Former Defence chief appointed new USC Chancellor {{!}} Business Moreton Bay Region|website=www.mbrit.com.au|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/it-took-a-combined-effort-to-make-our-university-a/3206099/|title=It took a combined effort to make our university a reality|work=Sunshine Coast Daily|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref> Air Chief Marshal [[Angus Houston|Sir Angus Houston]] AK, AFC (Ret\u2019d) became the university's fourth chancellor when he was appointed to the role in 2017 after John Dobson OAM retired from the position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/national/queensland/sir-angus-houston-appointed-university-of-the-sunshine-coast-chancellor-20170303-gupuzb.html|title=Sir Angus Houston appointed University of the Sunshine Coast chancellor|last=Mitchell-Whittington|first=Amy|date=2017-03-03|website=Brisbane Times|language=en|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mbrit.com.au/blog-news/former-defence-chief-appointed-new-usc-chancellor|title=Former Defence chief appointed new USC Chancellor {{!}} Business Moreton Bay Region|website=www.mbrit.com.au|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> Sir Angus remains the University's current chancellor.\n\nThe student body has grown consistently since the university opened in 1996 with an intake of 524 students. In 2017, USC had 16,692 students enrolled, a 13.6 percent increase on the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/documents/tableOffice/TabledPapers/2018/5618T437.pdf|title=Qld Parliament tabled documents|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe university introduced paid parking at its Sippy Downs campus from February 2013, a move that garnered a negative response from some students and staff. Of the university's 2,400 parking spaces, approximately 450 (located {{convert|1|km|mi}} from the centre of campus) remain as free parking.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox Australian university ranking\n| UniName    = \n| QS_W       = \n| QS_W_GER   = \n| THES_W     = 501\u2013600\n| ARWU_W     = \n| USNWR_W    = \n| LEIDEN_W   = \n| QS_AUS     = \n| THES_AUS   = \n| ARWU_AUS   = \n| USNWR_AUS  = \n| LEIDEN_AUS = \n| ERA_AUS    = 35<ref>{{cite news|title=All unis winners in research audit|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/higher-education/all-unis-winners-in-research-audit/news-story/a592cd109c087503ba4ea49cdf56c561|accessdate=21 February 2017|work=[[The Australian]]|date=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nSince 2010, USC has been the only public institution in Queensland to receive five stars for teaching quality in the independently ranked ''Hobson's Good Universities Guide''. In the 2010 edition of the guide, the university also earned five stars for staff qualifications and graduates' satisfaction with the generic skills they learned while studying.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/MediaPublications/News/MoreNews/UniversitiesGuide2010.htm USC gains top marks for teaching quality] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815182126/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/MediaPublications/News/MoreNews/UniversitiesGuide2010.htm |date=15 August 2009 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- independent sourcing for a claim such as this, please --></ref>{{update inline|date=November 2013}}\n\nIn the 2011 edition, the university also earned five stars for graduate satisfaction with the generic skills learned while studying, and four stars for access by equity groups, Indigenous enrolments, gender balance, and for graduates' satisfaction with their overall university experience.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2010News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm USC gains five stars for teaching quality] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928162534/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2010News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm |date=28 September 2011 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- independent sourcing for a claim such as this, please --></ref> However, the university only received one star for research grants, research intensity, toughness to get in, cultural diversity of the student body, success in getting a job, graduate starting salary and positive graduate outcomes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gooduniguide.com.au/ratings/compare/SUNSHINE_COAST?studyType=UG&institutionName=University%20of%20the%20sunshine%20coast&actionSearch=Search |title=How Sunshine Coast rates and compares |publisher=Gooduniguide.com.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>{{update inline|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe 2012 edition of the guide, released in August 2011, also awarded the university five stars for its graduates' satisfaction with the generic skills they gained while at university, and for Indigenous participation. The university scored four stars for access by equity groups, gender balance, and for graduates' satisfaction with their overall university experience. Its ratings for graduates' satisfaction also remained the highest awarded to any public university in Queensland.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2011News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm USC gains five stars for teaching] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104201647/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/NewsEvents/News/2011News/usc-gains-five-stars-for-teaching-quality.htm |date=4 November 2011 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- independent sourcing for a claim such as this, please --></ref>\n\nIn 2007 the [[Australian Universities Quality Agency]] (AUQA) audited USC as part of their assessment of all Australian universities. AUQA is a national agency that operates independently of governments and the higher education sector. The report commended USC for \"its significant achievements since inception\" and awarded USC commendations for the quality of the university's learning and teaching, student support services, workplace integrated learning program and degree approval process. The Headstart Program \u2013 a program allowing Year 11 and 12 school students to study one or more courses at the University, while still completing secondary school \u2013 and Global Opportunities Program \u2013 the University's study abroad were also acknowledged in the assessment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.auqa.edu.au/qualityaudit/reports/auditreport_usc_2007.doc/ |title=Australian Universities Quality Agency Audit 2007 \u2013 USC |access-date=27 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226112337/http://www.auqa.edu.au/qualityaudit/reports/auditreport_usc_2007.doc |archive-date=26 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nGraduates have consistently rated the university highly for educational experience, with a 92 percent satisfaction rating in the 2007 Course Experience Questionnaire.<ref>2007 Course Experience Questionnaire, conducted by Graduate Careers Australia \u2013 Overall Satisfaction Index, broad agreement{{Vague|date=February 2013}}<!-- Where is this published? --></ref>{{update inline|date=November 2013}}\n\nThe university's Global Opportunities Program received an award from the Queensland government at the Celebrating International Education and Training Industry Showcase in August 2007<ref>[http://www.premiers.qld.gov.au/Key_activities_information_and_services/International_students/Industry_update/Showcase/2007_Industry_Showcase/ Department of the Premier and Cabinet \u2013 2007 Industry Showcase] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080728170145/http://www.premiers.qld.gov.au/Key_activities_information_and_services/International_students/Industry_update/Showcase/2007_Industry_Showcase/ |date=28 July 2008 }}</ref> for promoting internationalisation.\n\nIn March 2008 the university was one of 99 organisations nationally and one of 10 in Queensland to earn an Employer of Choice for Women citation.<ref>[http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/Organisation_List_08.asp/ 2008 Employer of Choice for Women list] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090526084903/http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/Organisation_List_08.asp/ |date=26 May 2009 }}</ref> The citations are awarded annually by the federal government's [[Equal Opportunity for Women in the Workplace Agency]] (EOWA). It has received the citation for six consecutive years to 2010.<ref>[http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/2010/Documents/EOCFW_Breakdown_2010.pdf 2010 Employer of Choice for Women list] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001142540/http://www.eowa.gov.au/EOWA_Employer_of_Choice_for_Women/2010/Documents/EOCFW_Breakdown_2010.pdf |date=1 October 2011 }}</ref>\n\nSince 2006, the university has been awarded 17 citations from the Australian Learning and Teaching Council, recognising outstanding contributions to student learning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=All&state=All&tid= |title=Office for Learning and Teaching &#124; Welcome |publisher=Altc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823032108/http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=All&state=All&tid= |archive-date=23 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Six of the citations were awarded in 2009, with a further six citations awarded in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=2010&state=All&tid= |title=Office for Learning and Teaching &#124; Welcome |publisher=Altc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725154659/http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=2010&state=All&tid= |archive-date=25 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2011, a further five USC staff earned ALTC citations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altc.edu.au/award-recipient?recipient=&type=All&institution=7327&year=2011&state=All&tid= |title=Office for Learning and Teaching &#124; Welcome |publisher=Altc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Campus and locations ==\n\nThe main University of the Sunshine Coast campus is at [[Sippy Downs, Queensland]]. The university also has teaching facilities in [[Noosa]], and operates an education and research facility at Dilli Village on [[Fraser Island]]. The Sippy Downs campus is about {{convert|100|km|mi}} north of Brisbane. It is a 100-hectare flora and fauna reserve, and borders the [[Mooloolah River National Park]].\n\nThe Sippy Downs site was previously a [[sugar cane]] farm, at the geographical heart of the Sunshine Coast and its shires, close to the [[Bruce Highway]] and other major transport routes.\n\nThe buildings on campus have received 30 awards<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Architecture/Stages.htm Architecture awards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121054735/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Architecture/Stages.htm |date=21 November 2008 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No. INDEPENDENT sources for claims such as this, please. --></ref> for planning, architecture and construction. In 2000 the university received the [[Royal Australian Institute of Architects]] President's Award,{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} and in 1997 the Library was awarded the [[Sir Zelman Cowen]] Award for Public Buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://architectureau.com/articles/sir-zelman-cowen-award-for-public-buildings-6/|title=Sir Zelman Cowen Award for Public Buildings|work=ArchitectureAU|access-date=11 August 2017|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nAll buildings on campus focus on environmentally sustainable design to suit the subtropical climate of the Sunshine Coast. Buildings have been designed for passive lighting and natural ventilation to minimise the use of non-renewable energy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architecture.com.au/awards_search?option=showaward&entryno=2007040540 |title=Australian Institute of Architects \u2013 University of the Sunshine Coast Building H |publisher=Architecture.com.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.architectus.com.au/index.php?page=1014 |title=University of the Sunshine Coast Chancellery |publisher=Architectus |date=29 August 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, the university opened two new buildings, the A$12 million science building and A$13 million chancellery. In July 2007, the A$10 million indoor sports stadium was opened by Federal Education, Science and Training Minister [[Julie Bishop]]. A year later, [[Treasurer of Australia|Federal Treasurer]] [[Wayne Swan]] opened the A$13 million Health and Sport Centre, which has testing and research laboratories, a gymnasium and public psychology clinic.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Milestones/2007.htm Milestones 2007-2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007073249/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AbouttheUniversity/History/Milestones/2007.htm |date=7 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, construction started on a $5 million semi-industrial shared space facility for engineering and paramedic science students. This opened in May 2011 and has specialised equipment and large, open spaces suitable for medical emergency simulations and a wide variety of engineering tests and experiments. It also has several laboratories and tutorial rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/Boost-for-Engineering-Paramedic-Science.htm |title=Boost for engineering, paramedic science |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date=22 August 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144657/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/Boost-for-Engineering-Paramedic-Science.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also in August 2010, the construction of a child care centre on campus was announced, which will provide 75 child care spaces from early 2011.{{Vague|date=February 2013}}<!-- Now in 2013, does this centre exist, or were plans dropped? --><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/child-care-centre-to-be-built-at-usc.htm |title=Childcare centre to be built at USC campus |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144749/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/child-care-centre-to-be-built-at-usc.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, construction started on the university pool complex, which includes a 50m heated Olympic swimming pool for research and community use. The complex was officially opened on 19 October 2011, by Queensland Sport Minister Phil Reeves. Funding for the $2.1 million project was provided by the [[Government of Queensland|Queensland State Government]], the university, community donations, and through in-kind support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/minister-to-launch-usc-pool-construction.htm |title=Minister to launch USC pool construction |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144828/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2010News/minister-to-launch-usc-pool-construction.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Art gallery===\n[[File:USC Sculpture BETWEEN with USC Sport Centre in background.jpg|thumb|upright|Leonard Sabol, ''Between'' sculpture with USC Health and Sport Centre in background]]\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast Gallery hosts a range of exhibitions focusing on contemporary art and design. The annual exhibition program includes:\n*new media (including computer-based design)\n*photography\n*painting, drawing and sculpture\n*illustration\n*student exhibitions\n\nThe gallery is in the heart of the university campus, with more than half of the annual attendance being educational visitors (USC students and staff, U3A, TAFE, primary and high school students).<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/about/ USC Art Gallery.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104203538/http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/about/ |date=4 November 2011 }} Retrieved 13 December 2011</ref>\n\n====University art and sculpture collection====\nSince its inception, the University of the Sunshine Coast has worked to develop an art collection focusing on contemporary Australian art with an emphasis on Queensland artists. Many of these works can be viewed throughout the University campus. The University collection includes several sculptures in public spaces on the campus.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/collection/collection.htm#sculpture USC Art and Sculpture] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327143832/http://www.usc.edu.au/community/art-gallery/collection/collection.htm#sculpture |date=27 March 2012 }} Retrieved 13 December 2011</ref>\n\nThe University's collection of contemporary Australian Art includes one of the most significant collections of Western and Central Desert Australian Aboriginal Art on the Sunshine Coast.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/NR/rdonlyres/475E6C14-060C-46B9-B088-D071F0C4D5DE/0/WesternDesertEducationResource.pdf Western and Central Desert Australian Aboriginal Art on the Sunshine Coast] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419143113/http://www.usc.edu.au/NR/rdonlyres/475E6C14-060C-46B9-B088-D071F0C4D5DE/0/WesternDesertEducationResource.pdf |date=19 April 2013 }} Retrieved 13 December 2011.{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, you need an INDEPENDENT source for any claim that X is one of the most significant examples of Y.--></ref>\n\n===Netball stadium===\nThe university features an indoor arena used often for [[Netball]] matches and other sporting activities. Since February 2017 the arena has been the home stadium for [[Suncorp Super Netball|National Netball League]] team [[Sunshine Coast Lightning]]. The arena has a seating capacity of 2,200 and features broadcasting facilities and several corporate boxes.<ref name=Ref1>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/our-new-teams-striking-display-of-confidence/3078352/|title=Our new team's striking display of confidence|work=[[Sunshine Coast Daily]]|date=18 August 2016}}</ref> As a result of growing demand for the Lightning amongst the public, the venue was upgraded to 3,000 seats and also featured new change rooms, a function room, public bathrooms and an improved sound system; all of which was completed in May 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com.au/netball/story/_/id/25388195/lightning-buoyed-stadium-upgrade|title=Lightning buoyed by stadium upgrade|work=ESPN Netball|date=26 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation==\n\nIn 2012, the faculty structure at the university was revised, from three faculties each with a different number of schools contained therein, to two, each with three schools:\n\n*Faculty of Arts and Business\n**School of Business\n**School of Communication\n**School of Social Sciences\n*Faculty of Science, Health, Education and Engineering\n**School of Health and Sport Sciences\n**School of Nursing and Midwifery\n**School of Science, Education and Engineering\n\nThe University Council is the governing body with the chancellor presiding over council meetings. The council has 19 members including the chancellor drawn from the university staff, student body and wider community.\n\nThe academic board is the university's senior academic body. It advises the council concerning teaching, scholarship and research matters, formulates proposals for the academic policies of the university, monitors the academic activities of the university's faculties, and promotes and encourages scholarship and research at the university.\n\n== Research ==\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast's research focus is on regional engagement{{Vague|date=February 2013}}<!-- Sounds vaguely impressive, but what does it actually mean? --> and sustainability issues. In 2009, research efforts concentrated on applied genetics in primary production, regional sustainability and the health professions.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} The university has two core research groups; the GeneCology Research Group and the Sustainability Research Centre and an engagement centre, the Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise.\n\nThe USC Research Bank provides open access to the University of the Sunshine Coast's research output. The database ensures the research output of the university is accessible to local, national and international communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://research.usc.edu.au/vital/access/manager/ |title=USC Research Bank |publisher=Research.usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=28 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708153317/http://research.usc.edu.au/vital/access/manager/ |archive-date=8 July 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe university's research centres actively seek grants and funding, with the Sustainability Research Centre securing more than $2 million in funding in 2008, leading to the submission of more than 100 research papers.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} $1.3 million of that funding was drawn from the CSIRO's Collaborative Fund. In May 2009, a separate research team secured an AUSAID grant worth more than $500,000.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nIn June 2011 the university was announced as one of 12 projects to receive Australian government funding under the Collaborative Research Networks (CRN) program. In the period 2011 to 2014 the university will receive $5.45 million to fund research in water, sustainability, forestry and aquaculture.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/newsevents/news/2011news/usc-receives-5.45-million-to-boost-research.htm USC receives $5.45 million to boost research]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, you need independent sourcing for this kind of claim --></ref>\n\n=== Australian Research Council grants ===\nThe university received two [[Australian Research Council]] Discovery grants, worth more than $1 million, in the 2012 funding round announced in November 2011:\n* Scott Cummins was awarded a $656,377 ARC Future Fellowship for his study of primordial germ cell migration in perciform fish, titled: \"Decoding the rules of fate, attraction and cell migration in perciform fish\". The ARC grant will be coupled with Dr Cummins' ARC Discovery Project Grant for $145,000 over 2012 to 2014 for research into snail hypometabolism, enabling him to build a significant team of researchers conducting world-class research in the field of the biological sciences.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n* Roland De Marco, Pro Vice-Chancellor for Research and joint chief investigator in a project called \u201cNew mesoporous materials for use in high temperature proton exchange fuel cell membranes\u201d, gained a three-year ARC Discovery Project grant of $420,000, with $40,000 each year going to support a PhD student at the university. The research involves using [[synchrotron radiation]] techniques to develop innovative fuel cell materials with the potential to provide high energy and high stability alcohol fuel cells.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nOther 2011 ARC funding:\n* Kate Mounsey won a $375,000 competitive grant for research into the contagious skin infection, scabies, titled: \"A porcine model to provide new insights on scabies immunopathology\". Her study was one of 277 projects selected from 2,159 applications nationally for funding under the ARC's new Discovery Early Career Researcher Award (DECRA) scheme. The ARC grant will be coupled with Dr Mounsey's award of a National Health and Medical Research Council (NHMRC) Project grant of $483,510 (in collaboration with USC's Associate Professor Shelley Walton) on a related project over the same timeframe.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n* The university was announced as a partner in three successful ARC Linkage Infrastructure Equipment and Facilities grants, involving Cummins (via the [[University of Queensland]]), De Marco (via [[Curtin University]]) and Senior Lecturer in Environmental Microbiology, Ipek Kurtboke (via the University of Queensland).{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\n=== Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise ===\nThe Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise (CHASE) undertakes research and related activities in preventative health and rehabilitation, and understanding and enhancing sports performance. Projects include consultancies and tenders, conducting short courses and conferences and contributing to policy debate in areas such as biomechanical assessment, physiological profiling, sports coach education, and the implementation of healthy programs.<ref>[http://www.usc.edu.au/Research/atUSC/Centres/CHASE/ The Centre for Healthy Activities, Sport and Exercise] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211180638/http://www.usc.edu.au/Research/atUSC/Centres/CHASE/ |date=11 February 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== GeneCology Research Group ===\nThe GeneCology Research Group operates in the areas of genetics, ecology, genomics and physiology and the interaction between these. The research group researches sustainable production of aquaculture, horticulture and forestry systems, biodiversity conservation and sustainable urban forestry and horticulture.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/GeneCology/ |title=The GeneCology Research Group |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date=10 September 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104201310/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/GeneCology/ |archive-date=4 November 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Professor in Aquaculture Biotechnology Abigail Elizur and Associate Professor in Aquaculture Genetics Wayne Knibb were involved in a project that resulted in the first-ever captive spawning of Southern Bluefin Tuna.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2009News/Invention261109.htm |title=USC research features in ''Time Magazine'' |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927144900/http://www.usc.edu.au/University/NewsEvents/News/2009News/Invention261109.htm |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The project was voted the second most important innovation of the year by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', behind [[NASA]]'s [[Ares I|Ares rocket]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1934027_1934003_1933946,00.html|title=The 50 Best Inventions of 2009 \u2013 The Tank-Bred Tuna|publisher=Time.com|date=12 November 2009|accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Sustainability Research Centre ===\nThe Sustainability Research Centre focuses on sustainable communities and sustainable environments, and the institutions that relate to them. The research focus is based around coastal management, climate change, water management, natural and cultural heritage, innovation, adaptive growth, and community wellbeing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usc.edu.au/University/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/SustainabilityResearchCentre/ |title=The Sustainability Research Centre |publisher=Usc.edu.au |date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104200642/http://www.usc.edu.au/university/AcademicFaculties/Science/Research/SustainabilityResearchCentre/ |archive-date=4 November 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== University-based organisations ==\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast has one subsidiary company \u2013 Innovation Centre Sunshine Coast Pty Ltd. At the northern end of the campus, this is the first stage of a planned technology park precinct for Sippy Downs.<ref>{{Citation| url = http://www.business.sunshinecoast.qld.gov.au/sitePage.cfm?code=sc-bus-and-tech-precinct/| title = Sunshine Coast Regional Council current projects \u2013 Sunshine Coast Business and Technology Precinct| accessdate = 25 May 2009| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110706122121/http://www.business.sunshinecoast.qld.gov.au/sitePage.cfm?code=sc-bus-and-tech-precinct%2F| archive-date = 6 July 2011| url-status = dead}}</ref> The Innovation Centre comprises a [[business incubator]] for start-up technology businesses and a [[business accelerator]] for established technology, knowledge-based, and professional service firms.\n\nThe Innovation Centre provides serviced office space, high speed optical fibre Internet connection, business development coaching and support. As of July 2010, the Innovation Centre has supported the start-up and growth of around 80 businesses, mainly in ICT, cleantech and creative industry sectors.<ref>[http://www.innovation-centre.com.au/company_all Innovation Centre \u2013 companies] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814160445/http://www.innovation-centre.com.au/company_all |date=14 August 2009 }}{{Dubious|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, you need independent sourcing for a claim such as this. --></ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main list|List of University of the Sunshine Coast people}}\n\nThe current chancellor  of the university is Air Chief Marshall Sir Angus Houston, a retired senior officer of the Royal Australian Air Force. Professor Greg Hill was appointed vice chancellor of the university on 1 January 2011.\n\n== Student accommodation ==\nThree student accommodation complexes are next to the campus in Chancellor Park. Varsity Apartments, UniCentral and The Village are privately owned and operated. All are within walking distance of the campus, linked by pedestrian pathways.\n\nEach accommodation complex has furnished apartments, some with Internet connection. The general layout in an apartment is a shared kitchen and living room, with four single bedrooms, each with its own bathroom and toilet. The complexes are gated and have barbecues, pools and outdoor sports courts (such as tennis/basketball and volleyball). Many of these units are shared units, however each student has his/her own bedroom and bathroom, only sharing the main living spaces. Many complexes also mix the residents between local and international students for a well engaged cross cultural experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.varsityapartments.com.au/accommodation/ |title=Apartments |publisher=Varsity Apartments |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Apply Now |url=http://www.unicentral.net.au/facilities |title=Student Accommodation Facilities |publisher=UniCentral |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thevillage.net.au/Facilities.html |title=Accommodation |publisher=The Village |date= |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nUniversity of the Sunshine Coast is serviced by [[TransLink (South East Queensland)|TransLink]] bus routes, operated by [[Sunbus Sunshine Coast|Sunbus]]. Services depart to Caloundra, Nambour, Maroochydore and Kawana, with connecting services to Noosa at Maroochydore's [[Sunshine Plaza bus station|Sunshine Plaza]] interchange, and connecting to rail services at [[Landsborough railway station, Queensland|Landsborough Station]]. Services enter and depart from the new [[University of the Sunshine Coast Bus Station, Queensland|bus station]] via the Green Link.<ref>[http://www.translink.com.au/greenlink.php About the University of the Sunshine Coast bus station and green link] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090720114024/http://www.translink.com.au/greenlink.php |date=20 July 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Queensland}}\n*[[List of universities in Australia]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|University of the Sunshine Coast}}\n*{{official website|http://www.usc.edu.au/}}\n*[http://www.universitiesaustralia.edu.au/ Universities Australia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20011006211147/http://www.innovation-centre.com.au/ Innovation Centre Sunshine Coast]\n\n{{Australian universities}}\n{{Australian university groups}}\n{{CDIO}}\n{{Sunshine Coast Lightning}}\n{{Suncorp Super Netball venues}}\n\n{{Coord|26|43|01|S|153|03|44|E|display=title|type:edu_dim:5km}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunshine Coast, University Of The}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the Sunshine Coast, Queensland]]\n[[Category:Buderim]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:University of the Sunshine Coast| ]]\n[[Category:Sunshine Coast Lightning]]\n[[Category:Schools in Queensland]]\n", "name_user": "Rachael1100", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_the_Sunshine_Coast"}
{"title_page": "Kenya Technical Trainers College", "text_new": "{{about|an educational Institution in Kenya|the television station in [[Rochester, Minnesota]]|KTTC}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Kenya Technical Trainers College\n|image           = KTTC logo.png\n|image_size      = 300px\n|motto           = Home of Technical Education\n|established     = 1978<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wanzala|first1=Ouma|title=Matiang\u2019i directs KTTC relocation from Gigiri site|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Matiang-i-directs-KTTC-relocation-from-Gigiri-site/539546-3399514-alja70z/index.html|accessdate=30 May 2017|publisher=Business Daily|date=29 September 2016|language=en-UK}}</ref> <br>As (Kenya Technical Teachers College)\n|type            = [[Public]]\n|principal       = Ms. Hilda Omwoyo\n|dean            = Mr. Agira Jeremiah\n|students        = 2,400\n|city            = [[Nairobi]]\n|coordinates    = {{coord|1|14|25|S|36|48|59|E|display=inline,title|format=dms|type:edu}}\n|colors          = {{color box|#654321|Brown}}{{color box|#FFFDD0|Cream}}\n|country         = [[Kenya]]\n|website         = http://www.kttc.ac.ke/\n|logo            = [[File:Kttcemblem.jpg|150px]]\n|address         = P.O.Box 44600 - 00100 <br>UN Avenue, [[Gigiri]]\n}}\n\n'''Kenya Technical Trainers College''' is a Nairobi institution of higher learning. It provides[[TVET (Technical and Vocational Education and Training)|Technical and Vocational Education and Training]] (TVET).\n\n== Location ==\n[[File:Kttcplaque1.jpg|thumb|260px|A plaque marking the college unveiling on Friday 16 March 1979 by the then President of the Republic of Kenya [[Daniel Toroitich Arap Moi]] <br/>{{smaller|(Click to enlarge{{\\}}read.)}}]]\nKenya Technical Trainers College is located in the Gigiri area of Nairobi, along Limuru Road and next to the [[United Nations Office at Nairobi|United Nations Office]]. Aa controversial proposal by the [[Government of Kenya]] would relocate the college to the Kenya Science Campus of [[University of Nairobi]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wanambisi|first1=Laban|title=Kinyua to oversee controversial relocation of Kenya Technical Trainers College|url=http://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2017/05/kinyua-to-oversee-controversial-relocation-of-kenya-technical-trainers-college/|accessdate=20 June 2017|publisher=Capital FM|date=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Murumba|first1=Stellar|title=Matiang\u2019i sets the stage for UN takeover of KTTC land|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Matiang-i-sets-the-stage-for-UN-takeover-of-KTTC-land/539546-3937606-9va31tz/index.html|accessdate=20 June 2017|publisher=Business Daily|date=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Teacher education programs==\n===Certificate courses===\n* Instructor Training Part I\n* Instructor Training part II\n* Certificate in Management of [[TVET]] institution\n* Training of Trainers courses\n\n===Diploma courses===\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education  (mathematics/business studies)\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education(Mixed-mode)\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education with [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]]\n* Diploma in Instructor Training\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education ([[Mechanical Engineering]]) Pre-service\n\n===Higher and advanced diploma courses===\n* Higher Diploma in Education Management ([[Kenya National Examinations Council|KNEC]])\n* Advanced Diploma in Technical Education\n\n==Non-teacher education programs==\n* Diploma in [[Automotive engineering|Automotive Engineering]] (Automotive Engineering)\n* Diploma in Civil Engineering (TEP)\n* Diploma in Building and Construction (TEP)\n* Diploma in Building and Construction (Upgrading from Graft to [[Diploma]])\n* Diploma in Information Communication Technology (ICT) ([[Modular]])\n* Diploma in Building Technology ([[Modular]])\n* Diploma in Civil Engineering Technology ([[Modular]])\n\n===Student Body===\nThe student body, represented by the Students of Kenya Technical Trainers College Organisation (SKETTCO). In 2018, John Koech received re-election as finance minister of the SKETTCO.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of universities and colleges in Kenya]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kttc.ac.ke Kenya Technical Trainers College official website]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1978]]\n[[Category:1978 establishments in Kenya]]\n\n\n{{Kenya-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{about|an educational Institution in Kenya|the television station in [[Rochester, Minnesota]]|KTTC}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Kenya Technical Trainers College\n|image           = KTTC logo.png\n|image_size      = 300px\n|motto           = Home of Technical Education\n|established     = 1978<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wanzala|first1=Ouma|title=Matiang\u2019i directs KTTC relocation from Gigiri site|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Matiang-i-directs-KTTC-relocation-from-Gigiri-site/539546-3399514-alja70z/index.html|accessdate=30 May 2017|publisher=Business Daily|date=29 September 2016|language=en-UK}}</ref> <br>As (Kenya Technical Teachers College)\n|type            = [[Public]]\n|principal       = Ms. Hilda Omwoyo\n|dean            = Mr. Agira Jeremiah\n|students        = 2,400\n|city            = [[Nairobi]]\n|coordinates    = {{coord|1|14|25|S|36|48|59|E|display=inline,title|format=dms|type:edu}}\n|colors          = {{color box|#654321|Brown}}{{color box|#FFFDD0|Cream}}\n|country         = [[Kenya]]\n|website         = http://www.kttc.ac.ke/\n|logo            = [[File:Kttcemblem.jpg|150px]]\n|address         = P.O.Box 44600 - 00100 <br>UN Avenue, [[Gigiri]]\n}}\n\n'''Kenya Technical Trainers College''' is a Nairobi institution of higher learning. It provides[[TVET (Technical and Vocational Education and Training)|Technical and Vocational Education and Training]] (TVET).\n\n== Location ==\n[[File:Kttcplaque1.jpg|thumb|260px|A plaque marking the college unveiling on Friday 16 March 1979 by the then President of the Republic of Kenya [[Daniel Toroitich Arap Moi]] <br/>{{smaller|(Click to enlarge{{\\}}read.)}}]]\nKenya Technical Trainers College is located in the Gigiri area of Nairobi, along Limuru Road and next to the [[United Nations Office at Nairobi|United Nations Office]]. Aa controversial proposal by the [[Government of Kenya]] would relocate the college to the Kenya Science Campus of [[University of Nairobi]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wanambisi|first1=Laban|title=Kinyua to oversee controversial relocation of Kenya Technical Trainers College|url=http://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2017/05/kinyua-to-oversee-controversial-relocation-of-kenya-technical-trainers-college/|accessdate=20 June 2017|publisher=Capital FM|date=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Murumba|first1=Stellar|title=Matiang\u2019i sets the stage for UN takeover of KTTC land|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/Matiang-i-sets-the-stage-for-UN-takeover-of-KTTC-land/539546-3937606-9va31tz/index.html|accessdate=20 June 2017|publisher=Business Daily|date=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Teacher education programs==\n===Certificate courses===\n* Instructor Training Part I\n* Instructor Training part II\n* Certificate in Management of [[TVET]] institution\n* Training of Trainers courses\n\n===Diploma courses===\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education  (mathematics/business studies)\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education(Mixed-mode)\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education with [[Information and communication technologies|ICT]]\n* Diploma in Instructor Training\n* Diploma in Technical Teacher Education ([[Mechanical Engineering]]) Pre-service\n\n===Higher and advanced diploma courses===\n* Higher Diploma in Education Management ([[Kenya National Examinations Council|KNEC]])\n* Advanced Diploma in Technical Education\n\n==Non-teacher education programs==\