{"title_page": "Oklahoma's congressional districts", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S. House districts in the state of Oklahoma}}\n[[File:Oklahoma Congressional Districts, 113th Congress.tif|400px|thumb|right|<center>'''The State's districts since 2013'''<ref>{{cite web|title=The national atlas|url=http://nationalatlas.gov/printable/congress.html|publisher=nationalatlas.gov|accessdate=February 2, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222045635/http://www.nationalatlas.gov/printable/congress.html|archivedate=February 22, 2014}}</ref></center>]]\n\nAs of the [[United States 2010 Census|2010 census]], there are five '''United States congressional districts in [[Oklahoma]]'''. It was one of the states that was able to keep the same number of congressional districts from the previous census (in the past, Oklahoma has had as many as nine [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] seats). Following the [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma|2018 elections]], a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Kendra Horn|challenger]] ousted a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Steve Russell (politician)|incumbent]], changing the congressional delegation to a 4-1 Republican majority.\n\n==Historical and present district boundaries==\nTable of United States congressional district boundary maps in the State of Oklahoma, presented chronologically.<ref>{{cite web|title=Digital Boundary Definitions of United States Congressional Districts, 1789\u20132012.|url=http://cdmaps.polisci.ucla.edu|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> All redistricting events that took place in Oklahoma between 1973 and 2013 are shown.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Year\n! Statewide map\n! Oklahoma City highlight\n|-\n! 1973\u20131982\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma, 1973 \u2013 1982.tif|400px]]\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma (metro highlight), 1973 \u2013 1982.tif|400px]]\n|-\n! 1983\u20131992\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma, 1983 \u2013 1992.tif|400px]]\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma (metro highlight), 1983 \u2013 1992.tif|400px]]\n|-\n! 1993\u20132002\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma, 1993 \u2013 2002.tif|400px]]\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma (metro highlight), 1993 \u2013 2002.tif|400px]]\n|-\n! 2003\u20132013\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma, 2003 \u2013 2013.tif|400px]]\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma (metro highlight), 2003 \u2013 2013.tif|400px]]\n|-\n! Since 2013\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma, since 2013.tif|400px]]\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma (metro highlight), since 2013.tif|400px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|United States|Oklahoma}}\n* [[List of United States congressional districts]]\n* [[Politics of Oklahoma]]\n* [[Oklahoma Democratic Party]]\n* [[Oklahoma Libertarian Party]]\n* [[Oklahoma Republican Party]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140222045635/http://www.nationalatlas.gov/printable/congress.html#ok National Atlas of Oklahoma's Congressional Districts]\n\n{{USCongDistStateOK}}\n\n[[Category:Politics of Oklahoma|Oklahoma Congressional Districts]]\n[[Category:Congressional districts of Oklahoma| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|U.S. House districts in the state of Oklahoma}}\n[[File:Oklahoma Congressional Districts, 113th Congress.tif|400px|thumb|right|<center>'''The State's districts since 2013'''<ref>{{cite web|title=The national atlas|url=http://nationalatlas.gov/printable/congress.html|publisher=nationalatlas.gov|accessdate=February 2, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222045635/http://www.nationalatlas.gov/printable/congress.html|archivedate=February 22, 2014}}</ref></center>]]\n\nAs of the [[United States 2010 Census|2010 census]], there are five '''United States congressional districts in [[Oklahoma]]'''. It was one of the states that was able to keep the same number of congressional districts from the previous census (in the past, Oklahoma has had as many as nine [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] seats). Following the [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma|2018 elections]], a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Kendra Horn|challenger]] ousted a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Steve Russell (politician)|incumbent]], changing the congressional delegation to a 4-1 Republican majority.\n\n==Current districts and representatives==\n\nList of members of the United States House delegation from Oklahoma, their terms, their district boundaries, and the districts' political rating according to the [[CPVI]]. The delegation has a total of 5 members, 4 [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] and 1 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! District\n! Representative\n! Party\n! [[CPVI]]\n! Incumbency\n! District map\n|-\n! [[Oklahoma's 1st congressional district|1st]]\n| [[File:Rep. Kevin Hern official photo, 116th congress.jpg|100px]] [[Kevin Hern]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]])\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | R+17\n| November 13, 2018 - present\n| [[File:Oklahoma US Congressional District 1 (since 2013).tif|350px]]\n|- \n! [[Oklahoma's 2nd congressional district|2nd]]\n| [[File:Markwayne Mullin official photo (cropped).jpg|100px]] [[Markwayne Mullin]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Westville, Oklahoma|Westville]])\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | R+24\n| January 3, 2013 \u2013 present\n| [[File:Oklahoma US Congressional District 2 (since 2013).tif|350px]] \n|- \n! [[Oklahoma's 3rd congressional district|3rd]]\n| [[File:Frank Lucas.jpg|100px]] [[Frank Lucas (Oklahoma politician)|Frank Lucas]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Enid, Oklahoma|Enid]])\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | R+27\n| May 10, 1994 \u2013 present\n| [[File:Oklahoma US Congressional District 3 (since 2013).tif|350px]] \n|-\n! [[Oklahoma's 4th congressional district|4th]]\n| [[File:Tom Cole official congressional photo.jpg|100px]] [[Tom Cole]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Moore,  Oklahoma|Moore]])\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | R+20\n| January 3, 2003 \u2013 present \n| [[File:Oklahoma US Congressional District 4 (since 2013).tif|350px]]\n|- \n! [[Oklahoma's 5th congressional district|5th]]\n|[[File:Kendra Horn official portrait, 116th Congress.jpg|100px]] [[Kendra Horn]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Oklahoma City]])\n| {{party shading/Democratic}} | Democratic\n| {{party shading/Republican}} | R+10\n| January 3, 2019 \u2013 present\n| [[File:Oklahoma US Congressional District 5 (since 2013).tif|350px]] \n|-\n|}\n\n==Historical and present district boundaries==\nTable of United States congressional district boundary maps in the State of Oklahoma, presented chronologically.<ref>{{cite web|title=Digital Boundary Definitions of United States Congressional Districts, 1789\u20132012.|url=http://cdmaps.polisci.ucla.edu|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> All redistricting events that took place in Oklahoma between 1973 and 2013 are shown.\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! Year\n! Statewide map\n! Oklahoma City highlight\n|-\n! 1973\u20131982\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma, 1973 \u2013 1982.tif|400px]]\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklahoma (metro highlight), 1973 \u2013 1982.tif|400px]]\n|-\n! 1983\u20131992\n| [[File:United States Congressional Districts in Oklaho